      <item>
        <title>Lo-Fi tips anyone?</title>
        <dc:creator><![CDATA[akabillposters]]></dc:creator>
        <description><![CDATA[
            <p>To add to that, make use of the new Offset control to bring elements even further off the beat.<br>
(I found I couldn’t really get the level of broken/sloppy/lazy I wanted using just the available 32nds and 24ths.)</p>
<p>In terms of sounds, go for acoustic kits. Mess with them, but use acoustic kits as the starting point.<br>
Rumble and rattle in a kick is good. Click, bad.</p>
<p>I’ve personally starting grabbing kicks, snares, rimshots, claps, etc… other Lo-Fi tracks, but also Jazzy R&amp;B (e.g. D’Angelo).</p>
<p>One more thing… use ghost notes and alternates. Don’t just use one kick, use a secondary kick intermittently, to add texture. Same for hi-hats, snares, rims.</p>
          <p><a href="https://disco.auxy.co/t/lo-fi-tips-anyone/7367/6">Read full topic</a></p>
        ]]></description>
        <link>https://disco.auxy.co/t/lo-fi-tips-anyone/7367/6</link>
